\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:summary}

Motivated by $\sim 2-3\sigma$  excesses recorded by the ATLAS and CMS experiments at the LHC after the Run 1 data taking stage
around a mass of order 140 GeV in the $\gamma\gamma$, $Z(\to \ell^+\ell^-)\gamma$ and 
$ZZ(\to 4\ell)$ samples used for Higgs boson searches, we have analysed the discovery potential of a second neutral Higgs boson in the BLSSM at the Run 2 stage
of the  CERN machine. We have confirmed that a double Higgs peak structure can be accessed in this framework, in all the aforementioned decay channels (for luminosities which can easily be accumulated over the lifetime of the LHC)
with Higgs boson masses at  $m_h\sim 125$ GeV and $m_{h'} = 140$ GeV, wherein $h$ and $h'$ are the lightest CP-even Higgs states of the MSSM-like and genuine BLSSM spectra, respectively.  

Furthermore, under the assumption that the aforementioned excesses are not confirmed by Run 2 data, we have studied the possibilities at the CERN machine of establishing signals of an heavier $h'$ state of the BLSSM. We have shown that a peculiar decay  in the BLSSM is $h'\to hh$ (i.e., into a pair of SM-like Higgs bosons), which can in fact be dominant from its threshold (at $m_{h'}\approx 2 m_h\approx 250$ GeV) onwards. Guided by existing Run 1 analyses in the $4b$ and $\gamma\gamma b\bar b$ channels, from which we have borrowed some of the aspects of the corresponding kinematical analyses, improved upon by BLSSM dedicated selections, we have confirmed that, on the one hand, the former signature is inaccessible whereas, on the other hand, the latter signature can be spectacularly visible, 
over a quasi non-existent background. Its irreducible component can  in fact vigorously be reduced by stringent cuts in the di-photon invariant mass centred around $m_h=125$ GeV, so that the $h$ and $h'$ masses can simultaneously be extracted. These results have been shown to hold over a wide mass interval, from, say, 250 to 500 GeV or so, and for standard LHC luminosities.

Combining all these results, and noting that similar  Higgs signals would not be available in the MSSM, we conclude that their extraction (alongside the SM-like one established already at Run 1), either around 140 GeV or anywhere beyond 250 GeV or so, would not only point to a non-minimal SUSY scenario, hence beyond the MSSM, but also possibly pinpoint  the BLSSM as the underlying EW
symmetry breaking scenario.

We have illustrated this by first performing a substantial scan over the BLSSM parameter space to assess the compatibility of
the model with Run 1 data and then by carrying out sophisticated Monte Carlo analyses mimicking a Run 2 setup 
using several benchmark points, all such parametric situations
being in fact compliant with current theoretical and experimental
bounds. 


